I have successfully implemented the C++ solution for the regret-based greedy stock trading problem with transaction fees. 

The core logic uses a minimum priority queue to track possible buy opportunities and regret scenarios:
1. Every day's price minus the transaction fee (`price - C`) is checked against the minimum cost in our heap (`pq.top()`).
2. If it is profitable, we execute the transaction by adding the profit to our total.
3. Crucially, when we make a profit, we push two values into the priority queue:
   - `price - C` (Regret Shield): This acts as a placeholder. If a higher price comes along in the future, it pairs with this "shield" to effectively undo the current sale and move it to the future day, saving the transaction fee.
   - `price` (New Buy Token): This represents the opportunity to start a brand-new transaction on the current day, assuming the original sell was successfully moved via the regret shield.

### Resulting `solution.cpp`

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <queue>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Optimize standard I/O operations for performance
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int n;
    long long C;
    if (!(cin >> n >> C)) return 0;

    // Min-heap to maintain potential buy costs and regret shields
    priority_queue<long long, vector<long long>, greater<long long>> pq;
    long long max_profit = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        long long price;
        cin >> price;

        // If the effective sell price (price - C) is greater than the minimum cost in the heap,
        // we can form a profitable transaction.
        if (!pq.empty() && price - C > pq.top()) {
            // Execute the transaction and add to total profit
            max_profit += (price - C) - pq.top();
            pq.pop();

            // Push the regret shield: (price - C)
            // If a future price is even higher, it can pair with this shield to "cancel" the current
            // sell and move it to the future day, strictly increasing the total profit.
            pq.push(price - C);

            // Push the current price as a potential future buy.
            // Due to C >= 0, (price - C) <= price, the min-heap ensures the shield is popped first.
            // Thus, this price will only be used as a buy IF the above sell is successfully regretted,
            // strictly enforcing the "at most one trade per day" constraint.
            pq.push(price);
        } else {
            // If no profitable transaction can be formed, the current day is just a potential buy.
            pq.push(price);
        }
    }

    cout << max_profit << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

